      <dsc>
         <c id="ref10" level="series">
            <did>
               <unittitle>Inventory</unittitle>
               <unitdate unitdatetype="inclusive">Circa 1940s-1970s</unitdate>
            </did>
            <scopecontent id="aspace_c8a1b991a36389be1fdd80ce1eb89b66">
               <head>Scope and Contents</head>
               <p>The Louis Chevalier Papers, the gift to Manuscripts and Archives of Professor Chevalier in 1982, consist of course material, research notes, reference files, student papers, clippings, photographs, manuscripts and correspondence relative to Chevalier's work on the history and demography of Paris. The files contain reference material for Chevalier's courses at the College de France as well as his books.</p>
               <p>The papers are roughly arranged in five subject categories established by Chevalier. The first category contains much research material on the ethnic make-up of Paris and on the history of immigration to the city. Files on immigrants from Brittany are particularly voluminous. A second category consists of files on the various sections and neighborhoods of Paris. Of particular importance in this category are two feet of 1946 household census forms for selected streets in Paris. Though the summary of the census has been published the rest of the raw data probably has been destroyed. (Because of the fragile nature of the forms this material has been microfilmed. Researchers will not be allowed to use the originals without first consulting the film.) The third and fourth categories consist of reference files organized by subject for two of Chevalier's recent books, <title render="italic">
                     <part>L'Assassinat de Paris</part>
                  </title> and<title render="italic">
                     <part>Montmartre du Plaisir et du Crime</part>
                  </title> respectively. The final category includes correspondence with Chevalier's American friends and colleagues.</p>
               <p>The material remains in very much the order Chevalier sent it with his notes of identification in place. No hardware has been removed and no preservation measures (except the microfilm) have been undertaken.</p>
            </scopecontent>
